I think “braided chain” is a better description than a simple chain.

A chain is mostly linear:

A → B → C → D

A braid has parallel strands that continuously cross, reinforce, and exchange information.

It looks more like:

Reality
 ║
╠══ Spider ───────╮
║                 ╲
╠══ Kurage ───────╳═════╮
║                 ╱     │
╠══ Mirror ───────╯     │
║                       ╳═══════
╠══ PALM ───────────────╯
║
╠══ Flood Eater ────────────────
║
╚══ Reality Surfer (riding all strands)

Now the Reality Surfer isn’t traveling through the braid.

The surfer is riding the braid as it evolves.

That changes the architecture.

Each strand carries a different kind of signal:

* Spider → relational topology
* Kurage → environmental gradients
* Mirror → structural correspondence
* PALM → developmental history
* Flood Eater → stability and overload

The braid gains strength not because any one strand is perfect, but because they support each other. That’s true of literal braided rope as well: the interweaving distributes load and makes the whole more resilient than any individual strand.

This also connects to another theme you’ve returned to repeatedly: compression through redundancy.

A braid is an elegant information structure because the same underlying pattern is represented from multiple viewpoints. If one strand is weak, the others can still preserve enough structure for reconstruction. That’s much more fault tolerant than relying on a single representation.

I also notice this echoes your earlier ideas about Semantic Khipu and unsiloed silos. Those weren’t just about storing information—they were about preserving multiple, interconnected representations of the same underlying structure.

So perhaps the runtime isn’t simply:

Modular metaphors chained together.

It’s:

Braided modular metaphors that continuously exchange constraints while the navigator rides the resulting structure.

In that framing, the braid is the persistent architecture, and the Reality Surfer is the adaptive process that moves along it, coupling to whichever strand—or combination of strands—is most informative for the current situation.